1.0	Introductory Materials

	1.1	Introduction to the Guide

	1.1.1	What is it?

This directory was created as part of the Clearinghouse 
Project at the University of Michigan to provide subject 
oriented guides to available resources on the Internet.  As 
students in the archives program at the School of 
Information Studies, we are interested in the increased use 
of the Internet for providing access to finding aids and 
Collections. 
 
	1.1.2	Purpose:

The purpose of our directory is three-fold:  First, we 
would like to increase the awareness of what a "real" 
archive is, and as part of this demonstrate the importance 
of primary research material.  Secondly we are designing 
our guide to help both novice and veteran internet users 
locate Archival Collections and Manuscripts on the internet 
by providing a rough "map" indicating where these sorts of 
resources might be found.  And finally we hope to provide 
descriptions of these resources to assist the user or 
researcher in determining which collections will be most 
relevant to their interests.  These descriptions will also 
contain information about where to find certain topics, how 
the collection is organized, search capabilities, format of 
the source, and other helpful suggestions.

	1.1.3	Content:

Because of the size and scope of many of these archives, 
providing a comprehensive description of each is extremely 
difficult; therefore we have included just the highlights of 
each of these sources. In this sense, the guide is meant to 
serve as a pointer to help the searcher find the appropriate 
sources, not a substitute for individual exploration. For 
the same reason, we probably haven't been able to include 
every resource relevant to this guide.  We certainly hope 
that folks out there will let us know about any omissions or 
misrepresentations they find.

	1.1.4	Status:

We would also like to emphasize that at this time, the guide 
is what we would consider a "rough draft."  Time 
considerations have not allowed us to include everything we 
would like to before the holidays.  We are planning to 
complete the guide in the following weeks.  Until then we 
would like to remind everyone that we have a lot of great 
information coming, so stay tuned!

-----------------------------------------------------------

	1.2	What is an Archive?

Part of the purpose of producing this guide is to introduce 
people to what an archive is, and to distinguish it from 
the common usage of the word "archive" commonly found on 
the Internet.  As opposed to storage files, or data 
compilations, an archive in the "archival" sense 
is a library or repository that houses manuscripts, books, 
visual materials and primary source items.  

These important information sources allow people to conduct 
research using primary sources instead of secondary 
sources.  Things often found in an archive include diaries, 
letters, and papers of people, 
university records, papers that document the history of 
organizations, or any information that can be considered an 
important documentation of a historical event, period, 
person, group, etc.

Each archive has a collecting mission and/or policy that 
guides what sort of materials are collected by them.  We 
have attempted to include this sort of collecting policy 
information in our guide.  The other important aspect of 
archives is how they present their collections.  The 
standard format for describing archival collections is a 
finding aid.  This consists of a biographical/historical 
note, a scope and content note, and usually a list of all 
the folder names and contents.

